Title: Predicting Cervical Cancer Through Patient Demographic Features¶

Group 12: Justin Jao, Kevin Le, Nawaratt Tonrungroj

1.0 Introduction¶

Currently, early diagnosis is the most effective way to improve cancer prognosis. However, adherence to screening recommendations is poor, and over 50% of patients are identified late stage[1]. Therefore, identifying specific populations at high-risk of developing cervical cancer is of great importance. Several factors are known to potentially increase risk of developing cancer, such as parity, smoking, older age, hormonal contraceptives etc.[1] - [2]. However, the presence of one or more of these risk factors in a patient is usually not definitively predictive of having cervical cancer.

We aim to answer the question:

Can cervical cancer be predicted using medical history? Specifically, can we use known risk factors to build a model for predicting cervical cancer?

We will be using the k-nearest neighbors algorithm to try and build our model. The cervical cancer dataset from the UCI Machine Learning Repository will be used. The dataset to be mined consists of clinical information collected from 858 patients regarding their demographic information, habits, and historic medical records.

2.0 Methods and Results¶

2.1 Rationale for Selecting Variables¶

Several unsuitable variables will be removed from the raw dataset, as they are redundant (for example, a binary variable asking whether patients smoked or not was removed, as this data is already captured in another variable recording how many years the patient has smoked), clinically irrelevant (e.g. time since last STD diagnosis) or of low quality (too many missing observations, or not contributing enough variability to results). The variables we selected are already commonly being used to diagnose cervical cancer by medical oncologists [1] - [2].

We chose Biopsy as our target variable as based on current clinical research, biopsies are the current gold standard in diagnosis[2].

A summary of the variables we will be using are:

To begin wrangling the dataset, we remove the spaces from the column names for easier manipulation.

In [2]:
#convert column names to data-wrangling friendly format
col_names_vector <-make.names(names(cervical_data_raw),unique = TRUE)
colnames(cervical_data_raw) <- c(col_names_vector)

The variables we will use for the classifier are then selected and any rows with missing observations are removed.

We also change the Biopsy labels here to more easily interpretable names, with the "0" being changed to "benign" (non-cancerous), and "1" being changed to "malignant" (cancerous). We also convert the target variable into a factor for ease of processing.

In [3]:
#select the variables we chose
cervical_data <- cervical_data_raw %>%
    select(Age, Num.of.pregnancies, Smokes..years., Smokes..packs.year., Hormonal.Contraceptives..years., 
           IUD..years., STDs..number., Biopsy)

#remove any NAs
cervical_data <- na.omit(cervical_data)

#change the Biopsy label 0 to "negative" for ease of reading
cervical_data$Biopsy <- str_replace(cervical_data$Biopsy, "0", "benign")

#change the Biopsy label 1 to "positive" for ease of reading
cervical_data$Biopsy <- str_replace(cervical_data$Biopsy, "1", "malignant")

#convert target variable into a factor
cervical_data$Biopsy <- as.factor(cervical_data$Biopsy)

The dataset is then split into a training and test set for proper model building. 75% of the observations are used for the training set to make the model, while the other 25% will be the test set used to test the models accuracy. A seed is set because the data partition will be random so the seed will be necessary for the results to be reproducible.

In [4]:
#set seed for reproducability
set.seed(1111)

#partition data into training set
training_rows <- cervical_data%>%
    select(Biopsy)%>%
    unlist()%>%
    createDataPartition(p=0.75, list=FALSE)
training_set <- cervical_data%>% slice(training_rows) %>% data.frame()

As we are comparing the predictors to Biopsy, the label, the bottom row and right columns can be used to see the relationship between a positive or negative biopsy result when compared to the predictors. The bottom row of histograms show the results of biopsy at different observations from the predictors. There is a separate plot for the spread for positive results and another plot for negative results.

We can see that there is no variable directly correlated to the Biopsy label (positive or negative). There are more negative labels (red) than positive labels (blue), but the overall distribution of points across labels are not obviously different across all variables. Thus, our model will likely not significantly rely on one variable, but a combination of all these variables.

2.3 Building the Classifier¶

Having done EDA, we can now construct the knn classification model. To begin, we must perform certain data preprocessing steps to ensure our model will be as unbiased and accurate as possible.

Firstly, the previously cleaned and wrangled data set is scaled to ensure proper centering and standardization of all variables, so that certain variables will not have more influence on the distances used for the k-nn classification algorithm.

In [7]:
#scale all the variables except the target label Biopsy
scaled_data <- cervical_data %>%
    select(-c(Biopsy)) %>%
    scale(center = TRUE)

#create a dataframe combining newly scaled data and target label Biopsy
scaled_data <- data.frame(scaled_data, Biopsy = cervical_data$Biopsy)

#preview data

Initially, the dataset has far fewer observations in the positive class. Therefore, upsampling is required to balance the number of observations in each class label.

Here we can see the effects of upsampling; it changes the number of observations in the malignant class from 35 to 480, the same as benign observations. This essentially gives a single malignant observation more voting influence so that benign cases do not completely influence the classification.

This training set can then made into arguments to be used for the model.

In [11]:
#split data into the x_train and y_train arguments for model building
x_train_upsample <- training_upsample %>%
    select(-Biopsy) %>%
    data.frame()
y_train_upsample <- training_upsample %>%
    select(Biopsy) %>%
    unlist()

A dataframe of k-values is made and used in the train_control function for cross-validation purposes. Only odd numbers were used to avoid any ties in the voting function of the knn algorithm. We then train our model with 10-fold cross validation to determine optimal values of k.

In [12]:
#create sequence of k values to use for testing
ks <- data.frame(k = seq(from = 1, to = 50, by = 2))

#set cross validation parameters for 10-fold cross validation
train_control <- trainControl(method = "cv", number = 10)

#set seed for reproducability
set.seed(4444)

#train model with 10-fold cross validation
knn_test_upsample <- train(x = x_train_upsample, y = y_train_upsample, method = "knn", tuneGrid = ks, trControl = train_control)

We can plot these values to visually assess accuracy of k across values:

#select appropriate columns for plotting
ks_accuracies_upsample <- knn_test_upsample$results %>%

ks_plot_upsample <- ks_accuracies_upsample %>%
    ggplot(aes(x = k, y = Accuracy)) +
    geom_point() +
    labs(x = "Value of k", y = "Accuracy of k") +
    geom_line() +
    ggtitle("Distribution of accuracy of k")

ks_plot_upsample
Out[13]:

We can see that k=1 seemingly appears to give the best accuracy, and larger k values decrease accuracy. However, setting k=1 is usually not a good idea, as this runs the risk of overfitting the data. Due to cross-validation tests being inconclusive as to the reason for accuracy changes with different k-values, a short manual analysis of a range of k-values was done to see why accuracy is continuously decreasing (no peak), which is quite an unintuitive result (we would expect this to level off or perhaps even worsen at some point). Models were made with a range of k-values to see what factors are decreasing the accuracy.

A training set with scaled but not upsampled observations was used to see what proportions of predictions were being made for k = 1, 3, 5, 7, 9 (the best candidates for optimal k-values).

<fct><fct><int><dbl>
benign benign 2970.57669903
malignantbenign 1830.35533981
benign malignant 00.00000000
malignantmalignant 350.06796117

The tests show that the model is predicting the label to be malignant more often as k-values increase, which causes a by-product of more correct predictions of malignant cases in combination with more false positives in total. Overall the accuracy of the model decreases as k is increased. Considering the domain problem, minimizing false negatives (predicting benign when it is actually malignant) would potentially be of greater priority, as the potential harm of missing a cancer diagnosis is more serious. And so we would want to maximize prediction accuracy of malignant cases. However, upon further experimentation, we see that further optimizing the model by increasing k to minimize false negatives yielded negligable increases in prediction accuracy of malignant cases, whereas the frequency of false positives (predicting cancer when there is none) substantially increased. And while less severe, the potential ramifications of being incorrectly diagnosed cancer can also be problematic (e.g. receiving intensive harmful treatment such as chemotherapy or radiotherapy, as well as unecessary costs to the health system).

Therefore, we decided to value a greater proportion of correctly labelled benign cases than a minimal increase of correct labelling of malignant cases. We thus chose the lowest valid k-value that gave the highest accuracy, which was k=3. K=1 was not used as, while slightly better, model accuracy results were nearly equivalent with k=3, and setting k=1 generally runs the risk of overfitting data.

2.4.0 Evaluating Classifier on Test Set¶

The final model with the chosen k-value can be made. The test set, after splitting the labels from the observations, can then be used with the model to evaluate its accuracy by having the model predict the labels when given the test observations. These are then compared to the actual labels to get the accuracy of the model.

3.0.0 Discussion:¶

The goal of our project was to identify risk factors predictive of cancer and to see if we could use these factors to build a model capable of classifying patients as likely having cancer (malignant) or not (benign).

Once the model was run with the optimally determined variables and k-value, a relatively high overall estimated prediction accuracy of 75.88% was found, with an additionally high 94.03% accuracy for benign cases predicted. Unfortunately, prediction accuracy for malignant cases was poor, with only 8.33% prediction accuracy.

Further analysis of the confusion matrix showed that the accuracy of the model may be due to a preference for classifying points as benign instead of correctly predicting a malignant case, which was our goal for the model; initially, our expected outcome was to build a classifier that could accurately predict whether a patient would have a positive or negative diagnosis of cervical cancer when given a set of observations based on our chosen variables. Unfortunately, our model was not able to achieve a very high accuracy in predicting malignant cases. Thus, after generating the model and testing it, we conclude that in terms of impact, the best purpose for our model is only to potentially identify cases where there is no cancer (characterizing subgroup populations not at risk for cervical cancer), as the proportion of false negatives was quite low. Accurately differentiating between patients who are likely to be positive or negative is likely not possible with our current model.

Potentially, this model could be used to screen out patient subgroup populations who are not high-risk, and do not need close medical attention/follow up, which could potentially be used to cut down on medical costs and free up valuable time of health professionals.

Further work could potentially be based on identifying irrelevant variables to filter out using more statistically rigorous methods. For example, future research could perhaps employ advanced dimensionality reduction methods to further improve model accuracy, such as in principle component analysis.
